<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ah, knight, now you see into the depths of my very own confusion. For I always believed the Koada'Dal to be creatures of gentleness, kindness, and purity, but then I hear tales of torture and murder of Tier'Dal within the walls of our fair city, when never had I, in all my long life, even suspected such of my King. Where are these dungeons to which the Tier'Dal are dragged and beaten and murdered? I would have writtten the tales off as lies, had I not heard the stories from so many different dark witnesses. Yes, the dark ones might lie, but lie in such numbers, some with no knowledge of the others who told such a tale? There is no &quot;good&quot; in torture or outright murder; there is no &quot;good&quot; in genocide. And, since violence is how so many &quot;lightbringers&quot; bring the light to Norrath, how are they any different from a Tier'Dal who spreads hate through violence? Both are evil. And in my mind, the worse evil is evil done in the name of good.<br>
<br>
I teasingly threaten a certain mercenary with my wrath, but in sooth, he has nothing to fear from me. (I hope he does not read this and guess my identity, or else my bluff will be called.) True, he harmed one of my dear coven sisters, but my way is not to repay violence with violence. My way is to teach &quot;goodness&quot; by example, through mercy. Laugh, if you will, but  if even one act of violence is prevented when an angry soul remembers an act of kindness from the past, then I have succeeded in spreading the cause of &quot;good.&quot;<br>
<br>
I have always maintained that all life drifts in shades of gray. As a result, I am an outcast. But I'd rather be an outcast than allow intolerance, hate, and self-righteousness to drive my actions. Those driven by such are evil, no matter what banner of light they carry.<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
